MICHAEL Ndubane burnt to death when his three-roomed house in Calcutta Village in Mkhuhlu, Mpumalanga caught fire on Sunday, 9 January. The 52-year-old was a Bushbuckridge municipal general worker in Mpumalanga and was in a wheelchair. His sister Busi (50) said they received a call from panicking neighbours, saying her brother’s house was on fire. She said they tried to kill the fire, but it was too strong. “They found him dead in his bed with horrible burn wounds. He looked to have been struggling for help. We leave everything in the hands of the police to find the cause of the fire. He loved people. He is survived by his two kids.” She said the funeral will be held on the morning of Saturday, 15 January at his home. Bushbuckridge Mayor Sylvia Nxumalo sent her condolences to Michael’s family and friends. “We urge the public to look out for one another, especially neighbours and vulnerable people. We also urge them not to leave gas stoves, fires and dangerous chemicals unattended,” she said.  Brigadier Selvy Mohlala said police were investigating.“Police received a report that a house was on fire and someone was inside. They found the burnt house with the victim inside, sitting on a wheelchair. They immediately contacted emergency services for help, but the man was unfortunately certified dead. Mohlala said the cause of the fire was still unknown. If you have information, call Detective Lieutenant-Colonel Duduzile Shabangu on 082 4692 569, or Detective Captain Prince Mokoena on 082 3199 843.